    {
      "id": "samisch_variation_6_c5",
      "title": "Theory: Black Sacrifices a Pawn with 6...c5",
      "description": "Digitized from PDF chunk parsed_pages_76_80.json",
      "textContext": "Extracted from Starting Out: The King's Indian.",
      "preparsedJson": {
        "game_id": "samisch_variation_6_c5",
        "white": "Theory",
        "black": "Theory",
        "event": "Chapter 5: Black Sacrifices a Pawn with 6...c5",
        "initial_moves": "d4 Nf6 c4 g6 Nc3 Bg7 e4 d6 f3 O-O",
        "interactive_section": {
          "starting_move": 6,
          "moves": [
            {
              "move_number": 6,
              "player": "W",
              "move": "Be3",
              "commentary": "The above variations all assume that White plays 6 Be3. In our fourth section we shall take a look at the alternative 6th moves for White, principally 6 Bg5.\n\nWhat are the main ways to combat the Sämisch?\n\nBlack has three distinct strategies.\n\n1) Black can strike in the centre in Benoni fashion with ...c7-c5. Over the last decade or so this has supplanted all other variations and become the main line of the Sämisch. This is the subject of Section 1.\nNOTE: The Benoni is a sister variation of the King's Indian which normally starts 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 3 d5 e6 4 Nc3 exd5 5 cxd5 d6 6 e4 g6 followed by ...Bg7. Variations in the King's Indian where Black plays ...c7-c5 and White replies d4-d5 lead to a similar structure.\n2) He can delay his central strike in favour of queenside play. The most common way to do this is to play ...Nc6, ...a6 and 8...Rb8 so that Black can play ...b7-b5 at a moment's notice. This is called the Panno Variation and is the subject of the second section.\n3) He can strike in the centre with the traditional King's Indian move ...e7-e5. This is the subject of the third sub-section."
            },
            {
              "move_number": 6,
              "player": "B",
              "move": "c5",
              "commentary": "It has long been understood that playing ...c7-c5 is one of the most desirable ways for Black to meet the Sämisch. It keeps the long diagonal"
            }
          ]
        },
        "sidelines": []
      }
